23 is the first attempt to understand their experiences as a whole and to establish the political, social and cultural significance and ramifications of the wartime refugee crisis. Drawing on original research by leading specialists from more than a dozen countries, it will become the definitive work on the subject and will appeal to anyone who wishes to understand how governments and public opinion responded to refugees a century ago.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xRefugeeszEurope. 4aInternational Relations 2020. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aAustria-Hungary.  aBalkan Muslims.  aBelgian refugees.  aBulgaria refugees.  aEast Prussia refugees.  aEuropean refugees.  aFirst World War.  aFrance's refugee population.  aGreek refugees.  aHabsburg Empire.  aItalian-speaking refugees.  aJewish refugees.  aLithuanian refugees.  aPolish refugees.  aRussian refugees.  apopulation displacement.  arepatriation.  aresettlement.1 aAmara, Michaël, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelova, Irina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDowdall, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrizzera, Francesco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGatrell, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHermann, Martina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein-Pejšová, Rebekah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKorzeniowski, Mariusz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeiserowitz, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMondini, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb